  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2376296476" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2376296476" />
    <a title="K" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/81232236-k"><img alt="K" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2376296476?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="K" class="user" itemprop="url" name="K" href="/user/show/81232236-k">K</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2376296476" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13199097790256873160">This is a really good book, but it&apos;s so dark and depressing that you sort of cringe as you go through it. The narrator, Ned Hall, is a bit of a mystery, even though he tells you about the depths of his life and his innermost thoughts. You don&apos;t know what he looks like, and you have no sense of what he&apos;d be like if you met him. He probably wouldn&apos;t be overly friendly, as he says he&apos;s awkward and shy. But he spent so much time in bars with men shooting the breeze, that he could possibly be very ch</span>
  <span id="freeText13199097790256873160" style="display:none">This is a really good book, but it's so dark and depressing that you sort of cringe as you go through it. The narrator, Ned Hall, is a bit of a mystery, even though he tells you about the depths of his life and his innermost thoughts. You don't know what he looks like, and you have no sense of what he'd be like if you met him. He probably wouldn't be overly friendly, as he says he's awkward and shy. But he spent so much time in bars with men shooting the breeze, that he could possibly be very chatty. And since he's smart enough to rise from tough roots to a graduate degree, he's presumably smart enough to have an interesting conversation -- though it's not clear he's willing to do that.<br /><br />The tale of a depressing, financially dying town (fictional Mohawk, N.Y.) built on a dying leatherworking industry feels right. It's very masculine, very drunk, and with severely limited scopes of action. Almost nobody gets out of the black hole, and Ned shows you why. At a time when we're all reading about the opioid epidemic in towns like Mohawk, this book explains what it's like to live there, both if you're stuck and also if you have enough brains and desire to get away.<br /><br />So, you have Ned. He's about 35 or so when he's narrating the book, and he's settled into a decent life, though you don't find out until the end what that life is. He's mostly telling the tale of his youth from about age 6-18. The first part he spent with his mother, as his father had walked out on them when Ned could barely remember him. His mother was devastated by her husband's abandonment, which was nothing short of scandalous in 1950s upstate New York. She kept it together for a while, working at the telephone company, but she eventually had a nervous breakdown. Ned actually tried to lie and say his dad was dead.<br /><br />The breakdown came because Ned's dad, Sam, came back to town and tormented his wife. Never ex-wife, and he wouldn't give her a divorce. He was one of the town's never-do-wells, perhaps the savviest of the lowlifes in Mohawk. He was a drunk who could sort of hold his liquor and a very angry man who could mostly hold his temper. And because he grew up in the town, he knows everyone. Experiences in World War II changed him -- or so Ned's mom said -- but it's unclear if Sam was ever anything else but a charming schemer, angry at the world. WWII might have just made him feel it was okay to act on every impulse.<br /><br />Anyway, Ned's life as an altar boy is interrupted first by a scandal at the church and then by the appearance of his father, who takes him in at about age 12 for about the next 2 years. The middle of the book chronicles those aimless days and nights for Ned, in which he was often left alone in an apartment in an old department store in Mohawk's dead downtown. Ned learned independence at a time when he was too young for it. He would odd jobs for people downtown (like the hairdresser), steal things when opportunity presented itself, walk into the greasy diner for food (on his dad's tab) and ride his bike through the town's parks and to the library. He had no friends. He also had to endure a lot of semi-good-natured smacking around by a father who wanted to toughen-up his kid and who forced him to tag along evening after evening as he made the rounds of the dive bars.<br /><br />The funniest parts of this book are the snappy dialogue between Sam Hall and his drinking buddies. Wussy, the only black man in town treated with anything resembling equality (and then pretty much only by Sam) gets the best one-liners, as the one guy who can really dish it out to Sam without too much anger coming in return. While Ned sees his dad as basically unbreakable -- able to fix anything, able to work long hours on a road crew and then drink 'til nearly dawn and then do it again, able to arm wrestle a muscular teen onto the floor -- Wussy shows us that Sam has no sense of direction in his car, has screwed up every relationship he has, and is a lost and wandering soul.<br /><br />Although Ned is the narrator, much of the book is about him wrestling with those contradictions about his dad. Ned definitely fears him, and he should. His dad is a terrible role model, and he's abusive to the son (Drew) of his girlfriend (Eileen), who he relentlessly calls Zero. Drew seethes with anger, and a series of blowups occur. There's a lot of violence in this book, much perpetrated by Sam on others, but lots of people get mixed up in drunken fights and revenge actions. It's very depressing.<br /><br />Both depressing and often hilarious are Sam's interactions with everyone else in town. Those characters and incidents will stick with the reader for a long time. There's Mike, the bar and restaurant owner who runs a tab for Sam and is tormented by his hateful fat wife Irma (great cook). There's Rod Heinz, the most lost drunk of them all, what might be called a "rummy" back in the old days. There's Tree and Skinny, the latter of whom is a gifted gardener and shiftless drunk. There's Jack Ward, another "townie" who married into wealth and isolation in a big house on a hill. There's Untermeyer the ageless bookie. There are a series of cops who try to catch Sam, and do, occasionally.<br /><br />Ned has few acquaintances of his own, and as would be the case with any lonely and sensitive boy, he chews over small incidents for years and years. He has one friend, Claude, who falls apart in his own way and is the vision of everything Ned avoids by eventually leaving town. There's Tria, the ill-fated beauty with whom Ned might have had a personal connection if he and she could have overcome their terrible parents and fears. And there's the endless lamenting about his two crazy parents.<br /><br />With the bulk of the story based on Ned's two years with his dad, things move quickly when Sam falls apart again, and Ned moves back in with his mom and the attorney she's having a clandestine affair with. If there's a hero in the book, it's the attorney, F. William Peterson. He rehabs Ned's mom, lends money to Ned repeatedly, and helps Sam and Sam's friends with legal troubles.<br /><br />Ned's escape comes with leaving for college and being lucky to have a high draft lottery number so that he can avoid the fate of his dad. The story is told after college, not in real time, as Ned looks back on how he barely managed to escape his apparent destiny in the the pool halls and dive bars of Mohawk.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13199097790256873160" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

