<div id="review_4027086062" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4027086062" />
    <a title="Otis Hanby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77496673-otis-hanby"><img alt="Otis Hanby" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594662428p2/77496673.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4027086062?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Otis Hanby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Otis Hanby" href="/user/show/77496673-otis-hanby">Otis Hanby</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4027086062" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10934515298858505028">&apos;The Risk Pool&apos; was everything I love about a well-told story. It was a slow read for me because the characters were so multidimensional I felt I had to read in small chunks, to give them all the proper time to develop. Once I was past parts one and two, and into the beginning of part three, things sped up and the characters you became acquainted with grew richer in complexity. By the time I reached the last page, I felt I had lived a lifetime with the protagonist. Richard Russo is by far a supe</span>
  <span id="freeText10934515298858505028" style="display:none">'The Risk Pool' was everything I love about a well-told story. It was a slow read for me because the characters were so multidimensional I felt I had to read in small chunks, to give them all the proper time to develop. Once I was past parts one and two, and into the beginning of part three, things sped up and the characters you became acquainted with grew richer in complexity. By the time I reached the last page, I felt I had lived a lifetime with the protagonist. Richard Russo is by far a superior writer in today's market.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10934515298858505028" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

